06768nam a22011055i 9781512823783DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128237837 a10.9783/97815128237832doi  a(DE-B1597)627885  a(OCoLC)1350571777  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR830.D37bZ54 2023 7aLIT0240302bisacsh04a823.009354808352223/eng/202209271 aZigarovich, Jolene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeath and the Body in the Eighteenth-Century Novel /cJolene Zigarovich. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b43 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Secularism, Materialism, and Death in the Eighteenth Century -- tChapter 2 Preserving Clarissa Eighteenth-Century Embalming Practices -- tChapter 3 Waxen Encounters Flesh, Anatomy, and Autonomy -- tChapter 4 Circulating Bodies Secular Mementos, Jewelry, and Hairwork -- tChapter 5 Osseous Matter Bones, Relics, and Mourning Miniatures -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDeath and the Body in the Eighteenth-Century Novel demonstrates that archives continually speak to the period’s rising funeral and mourning culture, as well as the increasing commodification of death and mourning typically associated with nineteenth-century practices. Drawing on a variety of historical discourses—such as wills, undertaking histories, medical treatises and textbooks, anatomical studies, philosophical treatises, and religious tracts and sermons—the book contributes to a fuller understanding of the history of death in the Enlightenment and its narrative transformation.Death and the Body in the Eighteenth-Century Novel not only offers new insights about the effect of a growing secularization and commodification of death on the culture and its productions, but also fills critical gaps in the history of death, using narrative as a distinct literary marker. As anatomists dissected, undertakers preserved, jewelers encased, and artists figured the corpse, so too the novelist portrayed bodily artifacts. Why are these morbid forms of materiality entombed in the novel? Jolene Zigarovich addresses this complex question by claiming that the body itself—its parts, or its preserved representation—functioned as secular memento, suggesting that preserved remains became symbols of individuality and subjectivity. To support the conception that in this period notions of self and knowing center upon theories of the tactile and material, the chapters are organized around sensory conceptions and bodily materials such as touch, preserved flesh, bowel, heart, wax, hair, and bone. Including numerous visual examples, the book also argues that the relic represents the slippage between corpse and treasure, sentimentality and materialism, and corporeal fetish and aesthetic accessory.Zigarovich’s analysis compels us to reassess the eighteenth-century response to and representation of the dead and dead-like body, and its material purpose and use in fiction. In a broader framework, Death and the Body in the Eighteenth-Century Novel also narrates a history of the novel that speaks to the cultural formation of modern individualism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDead in literature. 0aDeath in literature. 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aMourning customs in literature. 0aMourning customszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aRelics in literature. 4aHistory of Science. 4aHistory-Social/